      MoviePass
   =20
 =20

The most important point about MoviePass is that it never made sense. With =
MoviePass, for a brief glorious time=C2=A0starting in August 2017, you sign=
ed up for a monthly service that cost $9.95 per month, and in exchange you =
could see as many movies as you wanted in theaters.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CAny movie=
, any theater, any day,=E2=80=9D  MoviePass said.
The way it worked is that MoviePass just bought the tickets for you. Movie =
tickets often cost $12 or more. MoviePass did not own any theaters and did =
not have special discount deals with most of the theaters (it did with some=
); it just paid the full retail price. It was=C2=A0possible=C2=A0for you to=
 lose money with a MoviePass subscription, if you=C2=A0only saw a handful o=
f movies a year. But if you saw one movie a month, MoviePass was losing mon=
ey on you. If you saw one movie a week, MoviePass was losing a ton of money=
 on you. If you saw one movie a day, oops oops oops.
And in fact MoviePass was losing a ton of money. In  the first nine months =
of 2018, the glory days of this business model, it had about $192=C2=A0mill=
ion of subscription revenue =E2=80=94=C2=A0an average of more than 2 millio=
n subscribers paying $9.95 per month =E2=80=94=C2=A0and $424 million of cos=
t of revenue, presumably consisting mostly of full-price movie tickets, for=
 a gross loss of about $226 million.
  [1]
=C2=A0In round numbers, each customer paid MoviePass $9.95 per month, but c=
ost MoviePass $22 per month in tickets.
By July 2018, about a year after moving to unlimited movies for $9.95 per m=
onth, MoviePass was pretty much out of money. It  announced new=C2=A0plans =
to charge more for fewer movies, so it could lose less money; it also, with=
out announcing it,   started changing the passwords of its heaviest users=
=C2=A0so that they were locked out of their accounts and couldn=E2=80=99t s=
ee so many movies. (It eventually got in trouble with the Federal Trade Com=
mission for this.) By January 2020,  it was bankrupt. (Now it is  coming ba=
ck in some much less funny form.)
None of this was surprising; I am not relying on unusual=C2=A0financial gen=
ius or unfair hindsight when I say that it never made sense. Everybody knew=
 that MoviePass made no sense and lost money every month on every customer,=
 in part because its financial statements were public but mostly because th=
e whole thing went viral and=C2=A0everybody knows how much movie tickets co=
st. MoviePass was very famously a baffling business model, and its executiv=
es =E2=80=94=C2=A0particularly Mitch Lowe, the chief executive officer of M=
oviePass, and Theodore Farnsworth, the CEO of its parent company =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0would frequently be invited on television to be made fun of about how=
 they were selling unlimited $12 tickets for $9.95.=C2=A0=C2=A0
But another very important point about MoviePass is that, for a   while,  e=
verything was   like this. There was a period in the late 2010s when it was=
 fashionable to think that the way to build a successful company was by los=
ing money on every transaction. You would create a desirable product, offer=
 it at an uneconomically=C2=A0discounted price, and get lots and lots of cu=
stomers very quickly. This growth in customers =E2=80=94=C2=A0even money-lo=
sing customers =E2=80=94=C2=A0was the point. That growth=C2=A0would, for on=
e thing, attract lots of venture-capital investment, because VCs seemed to =
care more about rapid customer growth than they did about unit economics.
But there was also a business case for it, which is why=C2=A0the VCs were i=
nterested. The theory was that there were a lot of new marketplace business=
es with strong network effects and winner-take-all dynamics, so it was cruc=
ial=C2=A0to get lots of customers quickly. If you could do that, you would =
lock in a leading position in the business, and your customers would come t=
o rely on you. And=C2=A0then=C2=A0you could work out the unit economics =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0most obviously by raising prices, though you could think of oth=
er ways. Perhaps you would achieve some economies of scale when you got rea=
lly big. Perhaps you could strike some sort of deal with your suppliers to =
lower your costs. In particular, there was a popular view that customer=C2=
=A0data=C2=A0was really valuable =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthe  new oil=E2=80=
=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0and that if you ended up with a lot of data about a lot =
of customers you could find some way to make money with it. Sell ads to oth=
er money-losing startups, maybe.
This theory sometimes went by the name =E2=80=9Cblitzscaling,=E2=80=9D and=
=C2=A0it was part of the bull case for big-name startups like=C2=A0Uber=C2=
=A0Technologies Inc. and WeWork Inc.
  [2]
=C2=A0It was particularly associated with the venture investments of SoftBa=
nk Group Corp. and its Vision Fund.
  [3]
=C2=A0But the name that I often used for it around here =E2=80=94 which I=
=C2=A0borrowed from  Kevin Roose at the New York Times =E2=80=94=C2=A0was =
=E2=80=9Cthe MoviePass economy.=E2=80=9D Not because MoviePass was the firs=
t or biggest company to use this model, but because it was the funniest and=
 most obvious=C2=A0example. When you take an Uber, you don=E2=80=99t really=
 know=C2=A0whether Uber is making or losing money on the transaction. When =
you saw a movie with MoviePass, you knew.
And MoviePass was a quite vocal advocate for this theory. When interviewers=
 would make fun of=C2=A0Lowe and Farnsworth for how much money MoviePass wa=
s losing, they would patiently explain that, yes, right, the goal of a busi=
ness is to=C2=A0grow, and=C2=A0the way you make a business grow really fast=
 is by losing money on every transaction.=C2=A0So here is Lowe in July 2018=
:

I find it really fascinating that people believe that since you're losing s=
o much money, you don't have a long-term business model. Amazon lost money =
for 20 years. Netflix still loses money. And so this is the way you build a=
 big company.
And you know, if you look at the numbers, we've grown faster than Spotify, =
faster than Netflix, faster than all those other services. And that's what =
we've spent our money on. And you know, we'll continue to fund it.

Or here is  Farnsworth in June 2018:
I=E2=80=99d say there is absolutely more money going out than coming in. Wh=
ich is no different from a Spotify going through $4 billion [it lost $1.5 b=
illion in 2017]=E2=80=94not that we=E2=80=99re going through that=E2=80=94o=
r an Uber, or anyone else that=E2=80=99s a pioneer in the space. I knew we =
would go through hundreds of millions of dollars. We never thought differen=
tly.
And they were not really=C2=A0wrong; MoviePass really=C2=A0did=C2=A0grow ve=
ry fast, at a time when that was the main goal of a certain kind of company=
. It had 20,000 subscribers in August 2017, when it started charging $9.95 =
per month for unlimited movies (before that  it charged =E2=80=9Cbetween $1=
2.95 and $89.95=E2=80=9D); a month later it had 400,000, and  put out a pre=
ss release celebrating its growth=C2=A0and saying that, =E2=80=9Cthough exp=
ensive for the company in the short-term, it=E2=80=99s a significant benefi=
t and more convenient for customers.=E2=80=9D By June 2018, MoviePass had  =
more than 3 million subscribers.
A third important point about MoviePass is that, though it was a wonderful =
metaphor for venture-backed startups in the late 2010s, it was not itself a=
 venture-backed startup. It was a public company, more or less;=C2=A0it was=
 the main business of a company called Helios & Matheson Analytics Inc., wh=
ich acquired a majority of MoviePass in=C2=A0August 2017 and was responsibl=
e for cutting the price to $9.95.=C2=A0
This is important. If you are a startup and you go to venture capitalists t=
o raise money and you tell them =E2=80=9Cwe lose money on every customer, b=
ut we double our customer base every month, and eventually that has to be w=
orth something,=E2=80=9D and they say =E2=80=9Csure does!=E2=80=9D and give=
 you a billion dollars, then that is between you and them and God.
  [4]
=C2=A0But if you do that with public investors, then the US Securities and =
Exchange Commission and the Department of Justice might start asking questi=
ons, questions like =E2=80=9Cwell does it have to be worth something?=E2=80=
=9D and =E2=80=9Cwhy?=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Last week the Department of Justice=C2=A0unsealed an indictment against Far=
nsworth and=C2=A0Lowe, accusing them of securities fraud. From the DOJ  pre=
ss release:

The indictment alleges Farnsworth and Lowe falsely claimed that MoviePass=
=E2=80=99s $9.95 =E2=80=9Cunlimited=E2=80=9D plan =E2=80=93 in which new su=
bscribers could see =E2=80=9Cunlimited=E2=80=9D movies in theaters with no =
blackout dates for a flat monthly fee of $9.95 =E2=80=93 was tested, sustai=
nable, and would be profitable or break even on subscription fees alone. Fa=
rnsworth and Lowe allegedly knew that the $9.95 =E2=80=9Cunlimited=E2=80=9D=
 plan was a temporary marketing gimmick to grow new subscribers and, in tur=
n, artificially inflate HMNY=E2=80=99s stock price and attract new investor=
s. As a result, MoviePass lost money from the $9.95 =E2=80=9Cunlimited=E2=
=80=9D plan.
In addition, Farnsworth and Lowe allegedly made false claims that HMNY poss=
essed and used technologies =E2=80=93 like =E2=80=9Cbig data=E2=80=9D and =
=E2=80=9Cartificial intelligence=E2=80=9D platforms =E2=80=93 to generate r=
evenue by analyzing and monetizing the data MoviePass collected from subscr=
ibers. However, the indictment alleges that Farnsworth and Lowe knew HMNY d=
id not possess these technologies or capabilities to monetize MoviePass=E2=
=80=99s subscriber data or incorporate these technologies into the MoviePas=
s application.

Here is  the indictment. The SEC also brought securities fraud charges agai=
nst them in September; here are the SEC=E2=80=99s  announcement and  compla=
int.=C2=A0
I mean, sure? MoviePass always felt like a comedy routine to me: Everybody =
knew it lost money on every customer every month, so Farnsworth and Lowe ke=
pt getting booked on television, and they=C2=A0gamely went on TV and people=
 were like =E2=80=9Cyou lose money on every customer!=E2=80=9D and they=C2=
=A0were like =E2=80=9Cbut we make it up in volume!=E2=80=9D and everyone la=
ughed because that is a=C2=A0good joke. =E2=80=9CBig data!=E2=80=9D they=E2=
=80=99d shout, over howls of laughter.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CArtificial intelligenc=
e!=E2=80=9D And people would roll around in the aisles because that truly w=
as the height of financial comedy in the late 2010s. It was a pitch-perfect=
 parody of what SoftBank and Uber and WeWork were up to. Obviously=C2=A0Mov=
iePass wasn=E2=80=99t making any money off of customer data or artificial i=
ntelligence or anything else. (Its financials were public!) But it was a gr=
eat schtick.
So here is a Yahoo Finance appearance from January 2018, mentioned in  the =
indictment:

Interviewer: How are you possibly making money?
FARNSWORTH: Sure. Well, I think, people ask us that all the time. And we=E2=
=80=99ve known from day one, Helios is a =E2=80=A6=C2=A0analytics company. =
So when I first got together with Mitch, and we looked at all the data, the=
 analytics, what it was, that=E2=80=99s really what made us make the decisi=
on to invest in MoviePass.

Or the  SEC complaint describes one particularly rollicking standup set tha=
t Lowe gave:
On March 2, 2018, Lowe spoke at the Entertainment Finance Forum, giving a s=
peech titled, =E2=80=9CData is the New Oil: How Will MoviePass Monetize It?=
=E2=80=9D Even though MoviePass=C2=A0was not collecting basic demographic i=
nformation for all of its subscribers, Lowe falsely and misleadingly stated=
 that MoviePass collected =E2=80=9Can enormous amount of information=E2=80=
=9D regarding its subscribers, and that it even tracked its subscribers thr=
ough their phones. The following week, on March 12, 2018, Lowe issued an em=
ail apology to MoviePass=E2=80=99s subscribers, partners, and employees, sa=
ying that =E2=80=9Cthrough a mix of exuberance about our future and joking =
around=E2=80=9D he =E2=80=9Cmischaracterized how MoviePass locates [its] me=
mbers=E2=80=9D and explaining that MoviePass did not =E2=80=9Ctrack=E2=80=
=9D its subscribers. On March 13, 2018, Farnsworth sent Lowe a text message=
 that HMNY=E2=80=99s stock was =E2=80=9Ctanking,=E2=80=9D and that investor=
s were =E2=80=9Csaying the exact thing I was afraid of that we are not a bi=
g data company and we just admitted it . . . .=E2=80=9D While Lowe=E2=80=99=
s apology acknowledged that MoviePass gathered a more limited universe of d=
ata than it had previously led the public to believe, the March 12 apology =
did nothing to correct the misimpression that MoviePass was using HMNY tech=
nology and capabilities to analyze the subscriber data in MoviePass=E2=80=
=99s possession.
Obviously it wasn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0just=C2=A0a joke. When Lowe went to a conf=
erence and said that MoviePass tracked customers=C2=A0through their phones =
and collected and monetized lots of data, he=C2=A0was=C2=A0joking, but when=
 he=C2=A0admitted=C2=A0that he was joking the stock tanked and Farnsworth g=
ot mad. Prosecutors and the SEC argue that they=C2=A0weren=E2=80=99t=C2=A0k=
idding, that they were trying to deceive investors, and that it worked and =
investors were deceived. From the SEC:
In November 2017, HMNY issued $100 million in convertible notes and, in Jan=
uary 2018, an additional $60 million in convertible notes. In February 2018=
, HMNY also conducted a public offering of warrants, which raised approxima=
tely $97 million. These HMNY securities offerings coincided with Farnsworth=
=E2=80=99s and Lowe=E2=80=99s materially false and misleading public statem=
ents regarding MoviePass, and HMNY used the proceeds of the offerings to fi=
nance its investments in both HMNY and MoviePass.
But Helios & Matheson=E2=80=99s=C2=A0market capitalization peaked at about =
$300 million in October 2017; by summer 2018 it was below $50 million, less=
 than 0.1% of  Uber=E2=80=99s valuation at the time. Nobody took MoviePass=
=C2=A0that=C2=A0seriously.
It is an unusual=C2=A0sort of securities fraud. The basic allegation is tha=
t Farnsworth and Lowe were constantly asked if MoviePass could make money w=
ith a $9.95 unlimited monthly subscription, and they constantly said =E2=80=
=9Csure probably somehow,=E2=80=9D and it never did. Which is all true. But=
 also its financial statements were public, and more or less accurate. They=
 never claimed that MoviePass=C2=A0did=C2=A0make money. They just claimed t=
hat maybe one day it somehow could=C2=A0make money, with some hand-waving a=
bout=C2=A0big data and artificial intelligence.
They were totally wrong, as it turns out, and prosecutors allege that they =
never believed it themselves. But it was the sort of thing that everyone wa=
s saying. They were just doing what they were supposed to do, selling a pro=
duct below its marginal cost in order to get lots of subscribers quickly. I=
t worked really well, and they got a lot of subscribers quickly and lost mo=
ney on all of them, and then they went bankrupt. It was not a good idea. Bu=
t it was kind of what the market demanded.
Meanwhile they were flailing around in private trying to figure out how the=
y could=C2=A0make money. From the indictment:
On or about October 8, 2017, LOWE wrote FARNSWORTH and a team of MoviePass =
executives to ask them to brainstorm =E2=80=9Cideas=E2=80=9D about how to g=
enerate revenue: =E2=80=9CSo now that we have gotten into month 2 of our ne=
w pricing model we will need to create a plan on how we get from the usage =
level now to the desired profitable model in the future.=E2=80=9D
From the SEC complaint:
In March 2018, MoviePass hired a Chief Product Officer, whose main focus wa=
s to identify a break even business model and then explore how MoviePass co=
uld generate additional revenues outside of subscriptions. The Chief Produc=
t Officer quit less than six months later, after realizing that MoviePass=
=E2=80=99s business model would not work. The Chief Product Officer communi=
cated his views to Lowe.
Imagine what those six months were like for him. (=E2=80=9CExhilarating and=
 very challenging,=E2=80=9D  he said on LinkedIn.) What a weird job, figuri=
ng out how MoviePass could make money. It couldn=E2=80=99t! That was the wh=
ole joke!

