      FTX vs. Binance
   =20
 =20

If you were a salesperson at a big investment bank in August 2008, it might=
 have been a good idea to call up some hedge funds and say =E2=80=9Chey, we=
 are hearing some bad things about Lehman Brothers. Do you feel safe with t=
hem? Might be a good time to move your accounts over here.=E2=80=9D The hed=
ge funds might have believed you =E2=80=94=C2=A0you would have been correct=
! =E2=80=94=C2=A0and moved their accounts to your bank. You would have done=
 more business and made more money. At the end of the year, you could go to=
 your boss and say =E2=80=9CI won all these accounts from Lehman, give me a=
 big bonus.=E2=80=9D
And then your boss, if she was smart, would have fired you.
If you were the chief executive officer of a big investment bank in August =
2008, and your subordinates were doing that sort of thing, how would you ha=
ve felt about it? Three possibilities are:
=09Good: They were being aggressive about winning business, and winning mor=
e business is good.=09Bad: Investment banking is a genteel business, and ba=
dmouthing a competitor is rude.=09Very bad: The banking system was in peril=
ous shape, and doing anything to undermine confidence in the system =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0like, for instance, spreading rumors that a competitor was collaps=
ing =E2=80=94=C2=A0would have negative effects on=C2=A0your=C2=A0bank. If L=
ehman failed, or even looked likely to fail, you might be next. Better to p=
rop up confidence in your competitors than to tear them down. Not all the t=
ime! In good times, sure, compete fiercely. But in a crisis, be extremely p=
olite.

I think actual attitudes in 2008 were a mix of all three, but among smart i=
nvestment bank CEOs the third attitude was=C2=A0very prominent.=C2=A0In 200=
8, the job of an investment bank was not to win market share; it was to sta=
y alive. And staying alive was not a zero-sum game; each bank was more like=
ly to stay alive if its competitors did. The way to stay alive was not by c=
onvincing everyone that you were better than the competition. The way to st=
ay alive was by convincing everyone that=C2=A0everything=C2=A0was fine, tha=
t the system was fine. Bad news for one bank was bad news for everyone.
The crypto industry right now is interesting in that:
=09It has recently suffered a crisis in confidence, with falling asset pric=
es, contagion, rapid deleveraging and bankruptcies of prominent firms.=09So=
me prominent firms turned out to be scams and Ponzis, and it=E2=80=99s reas=
onable to assume that there will be more.=09There seems to be a very wide r=
ange of risk management practices, compliance, etc., and some prominent fir=
ms are probably=C2=A0much=C2=A0safer than others.

I think this poses a challenge if you are the CEO of a big crypto firm. Unl=
ike the big bank CEOs in 2008, you are probably on Twitter a lot. If there =
are negative rumors about a big competitor, do you take to Twitter to say =
=E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re not a scam like those guys=E2=80=9D? One advantage o=
f doing that is that=C2=A0you might win some business and harm a competitor=
; crypto is a smaller business than it was a year ago, so winning market sh=
are is very valuable. Another advantage is that=C2=A0you don=E2=80=99t want=
 people thinking that you=E2=80=99re a scam; saying =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re =
not a scam like those guys=E2=80=9D is one way to persuade people that you =
aren=E2=80=99t.=C2=A0
The disadvantage is that it is probably in your long-term interest for peop=
le to be confident that=C2=A0none=C2=A0of the big crypto businesses are sca=
ms. =E2=80=9CCrypto is full of scams and you can=E2=80=99t trust even the b=
iggest exchanges=E2=80=9D is a=C2=A0bad message for a crypto exchange to se=
nd; adding =E2=80=9Cexcept us, you can trust us=E2=80=9D=C2=A0does not help=
.
Also I suppose you might consider the truth or falsity of these rumors =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0maybe you should tweet =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re not a scam like t=
hose guys=E2=80=9D if those guys=C2=A0are a scam, or tweet =E2=80=9Cno thos=
e guys are fine=E2=80=9D if they aren=E2=80=99t=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0but I=
=E2=80=99m not sure that=E2=80=99s the most important factor.
 Anyway:

Simmering tensions between the crypto industry=E2=80=99s two richest execut=
ives are spilling over into the already battered digital-asset market.=C2=
=A0
On Sunday, Zhao =E2=80=9CCZ=E2=80=9D Changpeng, the billionaire chief execu=
tive of Binance Holdings Ltd. took to Twitter to announce plans to sell Bin=
ance=E2=80=99s roughly $530 million holding of FTT, the native token of Sam=
 Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s FTX. Binance and FTX run the world=E2=80=99s large=
st and seventh-largest crypto exchanges.
Zhao said his decision was triggered by =E2=80=9Crecent revelations.=E2=80=
=9D In a Nov. 2 article, news site CoinDesk said much of the balance sheet =
of Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s trading house Alameda Research is comprised of t=
he FTT token. FTT=E2=80=99s price fell in high trading volumes after Zhao=
=E2=80=99s announcement and traders rushed to withdraw funds from FTX.=C2=
=A0
Caroline Ellison, CEO of Alameda, responded on Sunday to the CoinDesk story=
 by saying =E2=80=9Cthat specific balance sheet is for a subset of our corp=
orate entities, we have >$10b of assets that aren=E2=80=99t reflected here.=
=E2=80=9D Ellison later offered to buy all the FTT tokens from Binance at a=
 price of $22. The coin was trading just above that level on Monday.=C2=A0
Prices of most cryptocurrencies fell on Monday, even as equities advanced.=
=C2=A0

Bryce Elder  writes that =E2=80=9Cthough CZ insisted that his actions were =
not =E2=80=98a move against a competitor,=E2=80=99 it=E2=80=99s worth notin=
g there is little love lost between him and SBF,=E2=80=9D and that=C2=A0=E2=
=80=9Cjust a few days ago, SBF was making rather pointed allusions to CZ=E2=
=80=99s probity,=E2=80=9D but that =E2=80=9CSBF=E2=80=99s reaction to the l=
atest development has (so far) been somewhat less adversarial.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0Roughly speaking, CZ seems to think that bad news for FTX is good news f=
or Binance, while SBF =E2=80=94=C2=A0who has spent a lot of this year=E2=80=
=99s crypto winter  bailing out=C2=A0failed crypto companies =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0seems to think that bad news for one crypto firm is bad news for all of =
them. You want to win market share, but mostly you want crypto prices to go=
 up.

