      Oh Elon
   =20
 =20

Three possible models for Elon Musk=E2=80=99s acquisition of Twitter Inc. a=
re:
=09Musk is a business genius, and will find a way to make Twitter much more=
 valuable. This seems to be   the theory of Musk=E2=80=99s equity co-invest=
ors, for instance.=09Musk doesn=E2=80=99t care about making money, but he=
=C2=A0has a philosophical commitment to promoting free speech and vigorous =
debate on Twitter, the modern town square. This seems to be  Musk=E2=80=99s=
 theory, sometimes.=09Musk is very=C2=A0rich and very addicted to Twitter, =
and buying Twitter lets him be the boss of Twitter and make his own experie=
nce more fun, or possibly=C2=A0less fun but in a way that feeds his addicti=
on. This was more or less   my original theory of the deal.

In Musk=E2=80=99s unfathomably long  first week or so running Twitter, he h=
as driven away and  threatened advertisers,   fired and then un-fired emplo=
yees who he needed to run the site, rolled out and then   rolled back=C2=A0=
a new verification service that  didn=E2=80=99t work,=C2=A0banned a bunch o=
f users for  making fun of him, and then taken to Twitter to  make fun of t=
hem. If this is business genius it is, uh, too early to see the results. If=
 this is commitment to free speech, it is an unusual view of free speech. I=
f he is having=C2=A0fun, it is an unusual kind of fun. (He changed the loca=
tion in  his Twitter bio to =E2=80=9CHell.=E2=80=9D) But if=C2=A0he is disp=
laying the symptoms of an advanced case of Twitter addiction then, yes, thi=
s is all exactly what you would expect. He spent $44 billion to buy Twitter=
 so he could win more arguments on Twitter.  John Ganz writes:
There=E2=80=99s a great part of the Marx Brothers=E2=80=99=C2=A0Duck Soup=
=C2=A0where Groucho says of Chico, =E2=80=9CHe may look like an idiot, he m=
ay talk like an idiot, but don=E2=80=99t let that fool you, he really is an=
 idiot.=E2=80=9D I let it fool me: I thought, like many others, Musk must b=
e concealing intelligence, albeit of a cunning and nasty kind, that allowed=
 him to succeed at business. But it now seems like he might be on track to =
tank Twitter in a matter of weeks and perhaps even damage his other investm=
ents. Brands above all want a sterile and nonthreatening environment for ad=
vertisement: they certainly don=E2=80=99t want to be associated with the ki=
nd of seediness that Elon=E2=80=99s fanboys hope becomes the dominant tone =
of the platform. Twitter has in fact been a great force for democracy, not =
because it helps us share ideas or rationally deliberate=E2=80=94God no=E2=
=80=94but because it shows the rich and powerful to be just schmucks like e=
veryone else. All the sweaty jokes and lame memes, all the crude and harebr=
ained ideas=E2=80=94that=E2=80=99s really him, that=E2=80=99s what he=E2=80=
=99s like, there=E2=80=99s nothing more to it!
I have to say I =E2=80=A6=C2=A0completely sympathize? If I had limitless re=
sources and people made fun of=C2=A0me=C2=A0on Twitter,=C2=A0I would like t=
o think that I would ignore them and keep working on my world-changing plan=
s to solve climate change and colonize outer space. And then when I succeed=
ed and adoring interviewers asked me =E2=80=9Cwhat do you say now to the ha=
ters who made fun of you on Twitter,=E2=80=9D I would say =E2=80=9Chonestly=
 Bob I never read them, I was too focused on changing the world, I am not t=
roubled by petty carping on Twitter.=E2=80=9D But realistically would I be =
tempted to buy Twitter, shut down their accounts and tweet zingers at them =
on their way out? Absolutely. What is the point of all that money if not to=
 win meaningless fights on internet message boards?

