<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The most important point about MoviePass is th=
at it never made sense. With MoviePass, for a brief glorious time=C2=A0star=
ting in August 2017, you signed up for a monthly service that cost $9.95 pe=
r month, and in exchange you could see as many movies as you wanted in thea=
ters.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CAny movie, any theater, any day,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29619421.264507/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uc2VjLmdvdi9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2NvbXBsYWludHMvMjAyMi9jb21wMjU1MjUucGRm/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cBceb99ee1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> MoviePass said</a>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The way it worked is that MoviePass just bough=
t the tickets for you. Movie tickets often cost $12 or more. MoviePass did =
not own any theaters and did not have special discount deals with most of t=
he theaters (it did with some); it just paid the full retail price. It was=
=C2=A0<em>possible=C2=A0</em>for you to lose money with a MoviePass subscri=
ption, if you=C2=A0only saw a handful of movies a year. But if you saw one =
movie a month, MoviePass was losing money on you. If you saw one movie a we=
ek, MoviePass was losing a ton of money on you. If you saw one movie a day,=
 oops oops oops.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And in fact MoviePass was losing a ton of mone=
y. In <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29619421.264=
507/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzEwNDA3OTIvMDAwMTI=
xMzkwMDE5MDA0NDgxL2YxMHEwOTE4YTFfaGVsaW9zYW5kbWF0aC5odG0jYV8wNA/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cB7e62ace0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the first nine months of 2018</a>, the glo=
ry days of this business model, it had about $192=C2=A0million of subscript=
ion revenue =E2=80=94=C2=A0an average of more than 2 million subscribers pa=
ying $9.95 per month =E2=80=94=C2=A0and $424 million of cost of revenue, pr=
esumably consisting mostly of full-price movie tickets, for a gross loss of=
 about $226 million.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0In round numbers, each customer paid MoviePass $9.95 per month, b=
ut cost MoviePass $22 per month in tickets.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By July 2018, about a year after moving to unl=
imited movies for $9.95 per month, MoviePass was pretty much out of money. =
It <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29619421.264507=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzEwNDA3OTIvMDAwMTIxMz=
kwMDE4MDA5OTI5L2Y4azA3MzExOGV4OTktX2hlbGlvcy5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
16103536" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;"> announced new=C2=A0plans</a> to charge more for fewer mo=
vies, so it could lose less money; it also, <em>without</em> announcing it,=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29619421.264507/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMDgvbW92=
aWVwYXNzLWNoYW5nZWQtc29tZS1wYXNzd29yZHM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTEwNzIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkY=
mdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMTA3Jn=
V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB24e859a0" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
  started changing the passwords</a> of its heaviest users=C2=A0so that the=
y were locked out of their accounts and couldn=E2=80=99t see so many movies=
. (It eventually got in trouble with the Federal Trade Commission for this.=
) By January 2020, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/29619421.264507/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzEwND=
A3OTIvMDAwMTIxMzkwMDIwMDAyMDU1L2Y4azAxMjgyMF9oZWxpb3NhbmRtYXRoZXNvbi5odG0/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB83cae07e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> it was bankrupt</a>. (Now it is =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29619421.264507/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cubnByLm9yZy8yMDIyLzA4LzI3LzExMTk2NzAxODAvbW92aWVwYXNzLWNvc3Qtc=
3RhcnQtZGF0ZS1tb3ZpZXMtY2luZW1h/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdca9d473" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 coming back</a> in some much less funny form.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">None of this was surprising; I am not relying =
on unusual=C2=A0financial genius or unfair hindsight when I say that it nev=
er made sense. Everybody knew that MoviePass made no sense and lost money e=
very month on every customer, in part because its financial statements were=
 public but mostly because the whole thing went viral and=C2=A0everybody kn=
ows how much movie tickets cost. MoviePass was very famously a baffling bus=
iness model, and its executives =E2=80=94=C2=A0particularly Mitch Lowe, the=
 chief executive officer of MoviePass, and Theodore Farnsworth, the CEO of =
its parent company =E2=80=94=C2=A0would frequently be invited on television=
 to be made fun of about how they were selling unlimited $12 tickets for $9=
.95.=C2=A0=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But another very important point about MoviePa=
ss is that, for a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
29619421.264507/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzI=
wMTgtMDQtMzAvY29tcGFuaWVzLXdhbnQtYnV5YmFja3MtdG8tYmUtZWFzaWVyP2NtcGlkPUJCRD=
ExMDcyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJ=
nV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTEwNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cB300d6a82" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">  while</a>, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/29619421.264507/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW=
9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDUtMTgvc2lsaWNvbi12YWxsZXktcy1zdWJzY3JpcHRpb24tZnJlZ=
S1mb3ItYWxsP2NtcGlkPUJCRDExMDcyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRt=
X3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTEwNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHV=
mZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB098855a6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> everything</a> was <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29619421.264507/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDMtMjcvbGVhdmluZy10=
aGUtZW5jaGFudGVkLWZvcmVzdC1pcy1zY2FyeT9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMTA3MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ=
1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjExMDcmdX=
RtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc978b63a" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
  like this</a>. There was a period in the late 2010s when it was fashionab=
le to think that the way to build a successful company was by losing money =
on every transaction. You would create a desirable product, offer it at an =
uneconomically=C2=A0discounted price, and get lots and lots of customers ve=
ry quickly. This growth in customers =E2=80=94=C2=A0even money-losing custo=
mers =E2=80=94=C2=A0was the point. That growth=C2=A0would, for one thing, a=
ttract lots of venture-capital investment, because VCs seemed to care more =
about rapid customer growth than they did about unit economics.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there was also a business case for it, whi=
ch is why<em>=C2=A0</em>the VCs were interested. The theory was that there =
were a lot of new marketplace businesses with strong network effects and wi=
nner-take-all dynamics, so it was crucial=C2=A0to get lots of customers qui=
ckly. If you could do that, you would lock in a leading position in the bus=
iness, and your customers would come to rely on you. And=C2=A0<em>then=C2=
=A0</em>you could work out the unit economics =E2=80=94=C2=A0most obviously=
 by raising prices, though you could think of other ways. Perhaps you would=
 achieve some economies of scale when you got really big. Perhaps you could=
 strike some sort of deal with your suppliers to lower your costs. In parti=
cular, there was a popular view that customer=C2=A0data<em>=C2=A0</em>was r=
eally valuable =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthe <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/29619421.264507/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud2lyZWQuY29tL2luc2=
lnaHRzLzIwMTQvMDcvZGF0YS1uZXctb2lsLWRpZ2l0YWwtZWNvbm9teS8/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cB5a287008" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;"> new oil</a>=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0and that if =
you ended up with a lot of data about a lot of customers you could find som=
e way to make money with it. Sell ads to other money-losing startups, maybe=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This theory sometimes went by the name =E2=80=
=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29619421.264507=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDEtMzEvZG=
9uLXQtYmxpdHpzY2FsZS1hZ2FpbnN0LXlvdXJzZWxmP2NtcGlkPUJCRDExMDcyMl9NT05FWVNUV=
UZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTEw=
NyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa5a319bb" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;">blitzscaling</a>,=E2=80=9D and=C2=A0it was part of the bull case for big=
-name startups like=C2=A0Uber=C2=A0Technologies Inc. and WeWork Inc.<a clas=
s=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
