"> Uber=E2=80=99s valuation</a> at the time. Nobody took MoviePass=C2=A0<em=
>that=C2=A0</em>seriously.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is an unusual=C2=A0sort of securities fraud=
. The basic allegation is that Farnsworth and Lowe were constantly asked if=
 MoviePass could make money with a $9.95 unlimited monthly subscription, an=
d they constantly said =E2=80=9Csure probably somehow,=E2=80=9D and it neve=
r did. Which is all true. But also its financial statements were public, an=
d more or less accurate. They never claimed that MoviePass=C2=A0<em>did=C2=
=A0</em>make money. They just claimed that maybe <em>one day</em> it someho=
w <em>could=C2=A0</em>make money, with some hand-waving about=C2=A0big data=
 and artificial intelligence.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">They were totally wrong, as it turns out, and =
prosecutors allege that they never believed it themselves. But it was the s=
ort of thing that everyone was saying. They were just doing what they were =
supposed to do, selling a product below its marginal cost in order to get l=
ots of subscribers quickly. It worked really well, and they got a lot of su=
bscribers quickly and lost money on all of them, and then they went bankrup=
t. It was not a good idea. But it was kind of what the market demanded.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile they were flailing around in private=
 trying to figure out how they <em>could=C2=A0</em>make money. From the ind=
ictment:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On or about October 8, 2017, LOWE =
wrote FARNSWORTH and a team of MoviePass executives to ask them to brainsto=
rm =E2=80=9Cideas=E2=80=9D about how to generate revenue: =E2=80=9CSo now t=
hat we have gotten into month 2 of our new pricing model we will need to cr=
eate a plan on how we get from the usage level now to the desired profitabl=
e model in the future.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From the SEC complaint:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In March 2018, MoviePass hired a C=
hief Product Officer, whose main focus was to identify a break even busines=
s model and then explore how MoviePass could generate additional revenues o=
utside of subscriptions. The Chief Product Officer quit less than six month=
s later, after realizing that MoviePass=E2=80=99s business model would not =
work. The Chief Product Officer communicated his views to Lowe.</p></blockq=
uote>
